# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Codex Remote on Railway — app service variables
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Copy the values you need into the Railway service "Variables" tab (NOT into
# a committed .env file). The IaC (.railway/railway.ts) sets the non-secret
# defaults for you; the entries below marked as SECRET must be set manually
# because IaC intentionally does not embed secret material.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# --- HTTP transport ---------------------------------------------------------
# Railway injects PORT at runtime; the entrypoint binds the app-server to it.
# Do not usually set this by hand.
# PORT=8080

# CODEX_LISTEN_HOST rarely needs changing. Default 0.0.0.0 so both the Railway
# public domain and the Tailscale interface can reach the app-server.
# CODEX_LISTEN_HOST=0.0.0.0

# --- Codex WebSocket auth (SECRET) -----------------------------------------
# Capability-token auth. Either set the plaintext token (recommended — the
# entrypoint derives the SHA-256 digest at boot and unsets the plaintext
# before exec) OR pre-compute the digest yourself and set CODEX_WS_TOKEN_SHA256.
#
# Generate a strong token locally:
#   openssl rand -base64 48 | tr -d '=+/' | cut -c1-64
#
# Then paste the SAME value into the local shell that runs the client:
#   export CODEX_WS_TOKEN='paste-the-same-value-here'
#   codex --remote wss://<host>:<port> --remote-auth-token-env CODEX_WS_TOKEN
CODEX_WS_TOKEN=REPLACE_WITH_STRONG_RANDOM_TOKEN

# Alternative — pre-computed SHA-256 hex digest, no plaintext on the server:
#   printf %s "$CODEX_WS_TOKEN" | sha256sum
# CODEX_WS_TOKEN_SHA256=REPLACE_WITH_HEX_SHA256_DIGEST

# --- Model auth (SECRET, one of the two) -----------------------------------
# The app-server makes the model API calls, so the credentials live on THIS
# service, not on the local machine.
#
#   Option A — API key (simplest):
# OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-REPLACE_ME
#
#   Option B — ChatGPT / Codex sign-in:
# Run `codex login` on any machine, then copy the resulting ~/.codex/auth.json
# into the Railway volume at /root/.codex/auth.json (see README). No env var
# needed in that case.

# --- Optional Codex tuning --------------------------------------------------
# CODEX_HOME=/root/.codex           # override config/auth dir (default shown)
# CODEX_LOG_LEVEL=info

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPTIONAL: Tailscale tailnet (recommended for the "connect locally" path)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# When TS_AUTHKEY is set the entrypoint brings the container onto the tailnet
# with Tailscale SSH enabled and the app-server becomes reachable at
#   wss://<TS_HOSTNAME>.<your-tailnet>.ts.net
# (Tailscale terminates HTTPS via MagicDNS + Let's Encrypt when you enable
# HTTPS certificates for the tailnet).
#
# Generate a REUSABLE auth key at
#   https://login.tailscale.com/admin/settings/keys
# so redeploys keep working. TS_AUTHKEY and TAILSCALE_AUTHKEY are accepted
# interchangeably.
#
# TS_AUTHKEY=tskey-auth-REPLACE_ME                     # enables tailnet + SSH
# TS_HOSTNAME=codex-remote-railway                     # tailnet node name
# TS_EXTRA_ARGS=--advertise-tags=tag:codex-remote      # optional extra flags
# TS_STATE_DIR=/var/lib/tailscale                      # persisted on the volume
